    <exercise id="fs-id1369997" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1452722">    <para xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id2818232">(a) A 200-turn circular loop of radius 50.0 cm is vertical, with its axis on an east-west line. A current of 100 A circulates clockwise in the loop when viewed from the east. The Earth’s field here is due north, parallel to the ground, with a strength of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mn>T</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{3 "." "00" times "10" rSup { size 8{ - 5} } `T} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. What are the direction and magnitude of the torque on the loop? (b) Does this device have any practical applications as a motor?</para></problem></exercise>
    <exercise xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="fs-id2089664" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1617122">    <para id="import-auto-id1703539">Repeat <link target-id="fs-id1615066"/>, but with the loop lying flat on the ground with its current circulating counterclockwise (when viewed from above) in a location where the Earth’s field is north, but at an angle <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>45</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0º</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"45" "." 0°} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> below the horizontal and with a strength of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>6.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mn>T</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{6 "." "00" times "10" rSup { size 8{ - 5} } `T} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1354445">
    <para id="import-auto-id2902490">(a) <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>0.666 N</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">⋅</m:mo><m:mn>m</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{0 "." "666"`N cdot m} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> west
    </para><para id="eip-id1562323">(b) This is not a very significant torque, so practical use would be limited. Also, the current would need to be alternated to make the loop rotate (otherwise it would oscillate).
